```

the last sentence:

```
            renderable.shader = shaderProvider.getShader(renderable);
```

will make this one 

```
            renderable.shader = shader;
```

unusable.

In `com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.GlyoutLayout.java`, the method `adjustLastGlyph` defined as:

``` java
    /** Adjusts the xadvance of the last glyph to use its width instead of xadvance. */
    private void adjustLastGlyph (BitmapFontData fontData, GlyphRun run) {
        Glyph last = run.glyphs.peek();
        if (fontData.isWhitespace((char)last.id)) return; // Can happen when doing truncate.
        float width = (last.xoffset + last.width) * fontData.scaleX - fontData.padRight;
        run.width += width - run.xAdvances.peek(); // Can cause the run width to be > targetWidth, but the problem is minimal.
        run.xAdvances.set(run.xAdvances.size - 1, width);
    }
```

I noticed the comment:  `Can cause the run width to be > targetWidth, but the problem is minimal.` I do not think the problem is minimal, as every CJK character is a `breakChar`. It makes CJK rendering usually exceed bounds. Eg:

``` java
public class LabelTest extends ApplicationAdapter {
    BitmapFont font;
    Stage stage;
    Label label;
    Skin skin;

    @Override
    public void create() {
        FreeTypeFontParameter para = new FreeTypeFontParameter();
        para.size = 18;
        para.characters = "" + FreeTypeFontGenerator.DEFAULT_CHARS;
        font = new FreeTypeFontGenerator(Gdx.files.internal("yahei.ttf")).generateFont(para);
        font.getData().breakChars = para.characters.toCharArray();
        stage = new Stage(new StretchViewport(800, 600));
        skin = new Skin(new TextureAtlas(Gdx.files.internal("uiskin.atlas")));

        LabelStyle style1 = new LabelStyle();
        style1.background = skin.getDrawable("textfield");
        style1.font = font;
        label = new Label(" contain latin letters ", style1);
        label.setSize(150, 150);
        label.setAlignment(Align.center);
        label.setPosition(300, 300, Align.center);
        label.setWrap(true);
        stage.addActor(label);

        Gdx.input.setInputProcessor(stage);
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(int width, int height) {
        stage.getViewport().update(width, height);
    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        Gdx.gl20.glClearColor(0.5f, 0.5f, 0.5f, 1f);
        Gdx.gl20.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL20.GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act();
        stage.draw();
    }

    public static void main(String args[]) {
        new LwjglApplication(new LabelTest(), "LabelTest", 800, 600);
    }
}
```

The label in the test shown like this:
![qq 20151009143354](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8217836/10387288/dad1aca0-6e92-11e5-8aa2-a20fe6e5a67c.png)
It's obvious that it's right edge exceeds bounds. Maybe you would say I should not put every character into `breakChars`. Yes, I tried, but all CJK characters would be regarded as a single word, and the layout was bad.
